{"id":35,"parent_id":0,"book_id":22911,"content_id":1,"language_id":0,"display_order":35,"title":"Prophet Portrait: John Taylor","subtitle":"","short_title":"Prophet Portrait: John Taylor","uri":"/liahona/2013/03/prophet-portrait-john-taylor","content":[["div",{"id":"container","role":"main"},["div",{"type":"article","uri":"/liahona/2013/03/prophet-portrait-john-taylor"},[".heading",{"id":"head1","uri":"/liahona/2013/03/prophet-portrait-john-taylor.head1"},[".seriesTitle","Prophet Portrait"],[".title","John Taylor"]],[".bodyBlock",["p.para",{"id":"p3","uri":"/liahona/2013/03/prophet-portrait-john-taylor.p3"},["b","John Taylor"],"loved to",["b","sing."],"While in Carthage Jail, Joseph Smith asked Elder Taylor to sing “A Poor Wayfaring Man of Grief” (",["span.emphasis","Hymns,"],"no. 29). The song comforted the Prophet before his death. John Taylor was present at the Martyrdom, and even though he was shot four times, his life was spared. He carried a",["b","pocket watch"],"that broke during the Martyrdom. While serving in the Church, President Taylor edited many",["b","Church publications"],"and dedicated the",["b","Logan Utah Temple."]]],[".resources",[".figure",{"id":"f1","uri":"/liahona/2013/03/prophet-portrait-john-taylor.f1"},["img",{"src":"http://www.lds.org/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/fr13mar49-john-taylor-2013-02-05.jpg"}],[".credit",["p.para",{"id":"p4","uri":"/liahona/2013/03/prophet-portrait-john-taylor.p4"},"Illustration by Robert T. Barrett"]]]]]]],"refs":null}
